{
  "id": "019d2ed5-969c-7951-ba2d-230e5816dc02",
  "content": "## Forgetting Policy Configuration (#18) — Implementation Decision\n\nAdded `[forgetting]` config section to `corvia.toml` with a 3-level hierarchy:\nglobal defaults → per-memory-type overrides → per-scope overrides.\n\n### Key Design Decisions\n\n1. **`ForgettingOverride` shared type**: Per-type and per-scope overrides use the same `ForgettingOverride` struct (with type aliases `PerTypeForgettingConfig` and `ScopeForgettingOverride`) to avoid duplication.\n\n2. **Per-type `enabled=false` is a hard disable**: Scope overrides cannot re-enable a memory type disabled at the per-type level. This allows admins to guarantee certain types (e.g., Structural) are never subject to forgetting.\n\n3. **`resolve_policy()` takes `scope_override` not `scope_id`**: The caller looks up `ScopeConfig` by scope ID and passes the optional `forgetting` field. This decouples resolution from scope lookup — the GC worker (#19) handles the lookup.\n\n4. **Validation wired into `CorviaConfig::load()`**: `max_inactive_days > 0` is enforced at all three layers (global, per-type, per-scope) during config load. `budget_top_n = 0` means no limit (valid).\n\n5. **Default disabled**: `enabled: false` by default — forgetting is opt-in. Missing `[forgetting]` section = `None` (backward compatible).\n\n### Files Changed\n- `crates/corvia-common/src/config.rs` — All types, resolution, validation, 16 tests\n- `docs/rfcs/2026-03-27-forgetting-policy-config-design.md` — Design RFC\n\n### PR: chunzhe10/corvia#33",
